04406nam a22006855i 9781442685635DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192007onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426856357 a10.3138/97814426856352doi  a(DE-B1597)528793  a(OCoLC)1114888345  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a328.71/0722221 aSmith, David E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe People's House of Commons :bTheories of Democracy in Contention /cDavid E. Smith. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. The State of the Commons -- t2. Parliamentary Democracy -- t3. Constitutional Democracy -- t4. Electoral Democracy -- t5. What Is the House? -- t6. Who Are the People? -- t7. The People’s House of Commons and Its Study -- t8. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanada's House of Commons has come under considerable attack in recent years. Many critics have contended that the House has been unresponsive to public opinion, and that its party leaders have too much control, while leaving individual MPs essentially powerless. The House has also faced challenges by the courts since the introduction of the Charter, a powerful bureaucracy equipped with specialized knowledge, and new telecommunications systems that are redefining the transfer of information.Through an examination of academic, judicial, political, and legal commentary, The People's House of Commons explores the role of the House as a public institution. While addressing much of the criticism that has been levelled at the House, David E. Smith considers the competing political models and inherent tensions and their affect on public understanding. Smith maintains that court decisions are transforming the political system from one dominated by parties to one that promotes individual participation. He argues that reforms such as fixed election dates or stronger parliamentary committees have constitutional significance since their implementation would alter the practice of responsible government, which for more than a century has been a party government.A definitive work by one of Canada's foremost experts in the field of political science, The People's House of Commons explores the ramifications of many of the changes currently being proposed to Canada's political system, with particular reference to their affect on prerogative power, parliamentary privilege, party discipline, bicameralism, and the role of the opposition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDemocracyzCanada. 0aLegislative bodieszCanada. 0aPolitical participationzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268563540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442685635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685635.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK